    <title>Creating a containers-based application.</title><!-- can be changed via merge
in the assembly -->
    <!-- add author's e-mail -->
    <meta name="maintainer" content="jsindelarova@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract><!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
       By using &compose; you can create and start a container-based application.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <para>
  The procedure of creating and starting a container-based application can be summarized into the following steps:
  </para>
  <procedure>
    <step>
      <para>
Prepare the <filename>compose.yml</filename> file.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Optionally, prepare the environment variables file.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Use &compose; to start the application.
      </para>
    </step>
  </procedure>
  <section xml:id="compose-creating-application">
    <title>Preparing the <filename>compose.yml</filename> file</title>

<!--
   Do those container images need to present in specific directory, or do Podman pulls them from
registries.
-->
    <para>
      For a complete specification, refer to the <link
      xlink:href="https://docs.docker.com/compose/compose-file/">&compose; file specification</link>.
    </para>
  </section>
  
  <section xml:id="compose-creating-application-running-compose">
    <title>Starting the application</title>
    <para>
      In the directory, where <filename>compose.yml</filename> reside, run:
    </para>
    <screen>&prompt.root;compose up <replaceable>[OPTIONS]</replaceable>
    <replaceable>[SERVICE]</replaceable></screen>
    <para>
      The recommended option is <option>-d</option> as it starts the containers in detached state.
      Otherwise, the containers exit as soon as the command is terminated.
    </para>
    
  </section>
